Working on https://github.com/eclipse/eclipse.jdt.ls/pull/206, I noticed some inconsistencies in cursor handling when completionItems are returned as Text vs SnippetString

- VSCode Version: 1.11.1
- OS Version: 10.12.3

Steps to Reproduce:

1. When `@Override\npublic void run() {\n\t{{}}\n}` is returned  as Text
``` Received response 'completionItem/resolve - (336)' in 9ms.
Result: {
    "label": "run() : void",
    "kind": 3,
    "detail": "Override method in 'Runnable'",
    "documentation": "When an object implementing interface `Runnable` is used to create a thread, starting the thread causes the object's `run` method to be called in that separately executing thread.\n\nThe general contract of the method `run` is that it may take any action whatsoever.\n\n *  **See Also:**\n    \n     *  java.lang.Thread.run()",
    "sortText": "zzzzzziied",
    "insertTextFormat": 1,
    "textEdit": {
        "range": {
            "start": {
                "line": 5,
                "character": 1
            },
            "end": {
                "line": 5,
                "character": 2
            }
        },
        "newText": "@Override\npublic void run() {\n\t{{}}\n}"
    }
}
``` 
the above completionItem is rendered as :
![](https://content.screencast.com/users/fbricon/folders/Jing/media/967d02c6-3d41-4fb4-9dd9-c63bd7eb7a3e/00000004.png)

2. Now when returning `@Override\npublic String get(String t) {\n\t{{}}\n}` as SnippetString 
```
[Trace - 9:13:20 AM] Received response 'completionItem/resolve - (352)' in 8ms.
Result: {
    "label": "get(String t) : String",
    "kind": 3,
    "detail": "Override method in 'IFace'",
    "sortText": "zzzzzziied",
    "insertTextFormat": 2,
    "textEdit": {
        "range": {
            "start": {
                "line": 4,
                "character": 1
            },
            "end": {
                "line": 4,
                "character": 2
            }
        },
        "newText": "@Override\npublic String get(String t) {\n\t{{}}\n}"
    }
}
```
the `{{}}` is not rendered as cursor position
![](https://content.screencast.com/users/fbricon/folders/Jing/media/1b499018-2a5d-4787-aeca-164a040e160a/00000005.png)

I understand SnippetString is meant as a way to provide richer code completion with tabstops. I guess I could use ${0} instead, but why not supporting {{}} too? Why are there 2 syntaxes to provide cursor position? 

cc @gorkem
